"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Ezekiel chapters 36–38
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-ezekiel-36-38-fill.py

Christological themes:
- Ch36: new heart/new Spirit (v.25-26) → baptism + regeneration; ch36 v.27 already exists
- Ch37: valley of dry bones → resurrection; two sticks → one king David (Messiah);
  dwelling place among them (v.27) → John 1:14 / Rev 21:3
- Ch38: Gog of Magog → eschatological anti-Christ coalition; YHWH's direct defeat → Rev 19-20;
  universal recognition formula → Phil 2:10-11

merge_comm skips v.27 of ch36 (already present). 88 missing verses written.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZEKIEL_CHRIST = {
"36": {
    "1": '<p>Chapter 36 is one of the most Christologically rich chapters in Ezekiel. The chapter begins with restoration oracles to the mountains of Israel — the land itself addressed as a covenantal partner. Christologically, the restoration of the land is the material dimension of the new creation: "the creation itself will be set free from its bondage to corruption" (Rom 8:21). Christ\'s redemptive work is not merely spiritual but encompasses the physical creation (Rom 8:19-23; Rev 21:1-5).</p>',
    "2": '<p>The enemies who said the ancient heights have become their possession. The nations\' claim over the covenant land represents the anti-Kingdom forces. Christologically, the reversal of enemy possession of the covenant promises is accomplished in Christ: "the God of peace will soon crush Satan under your feet" (Rom 16:20). What the enemy claimed is reclaimed through the one who disarmed the powers (Col 2:15).</p>',
    "3": '<p>Made desolate and swallowed up by the nations — the covenant land despised. The cosmic scandal of the covenant promise appearing to fail. Christologically, the apparent failure of the covenant at the cross (the Messiah crucified, the promises appearing void) is the moment when the deepest purpose of the covenant is accomplished. "He was despised and rejected by men" (Isa 53:3) — and through that despising came the restoration of all things.</p>',
    "4": '<p>YHWH speaks to the mountains, hills, ravines, and valleys — the comprehensive geographical address. The cosmic scope of the restoration: every feature of the land is included. Christologically, the new creation is equally comprehensive: "all things were created through him and for him... and in him all things hold together" (Col 1:16-17). The one who holds the physical creation is the one through whom its restoration comes.</p>',
    "5": '<p>YHWH speaks in fiery jealousy against the rest of the nations, especially Edom. Divine jealousy as the protective love that refuses to let the covenant promises be permanently negated. Christologically, this protective love is expressed in Jesus\'s temple cleansing: "zeal for your house will consume me" (John 2:17 citing Ps 69:9) — the jealous protection of the Father\'s covenantal house.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The fire of YHWH\'s jealousy spoken to the land of Israel. The prophetic passion for the covenant\'s fulfillment drives the restoration oracle. Christologically, the divine jealousy for the covenant people is the background for Paul\'s statement: "I feel a divine jealousy for you, since I betrothed you to one husband, to present you as a pure virgin to Christ" (2 Cor 11:2). The apostolic mission shares the divine jealousy for the covenant community.</p>',
    "7": '<p>YHWH\'s oath to make the nations bear their shame. The divine oath as the guarantee of covenant fulfillment. Christologically, God\'s oath is the foundation of sure hope: "when God desired to show more convincingly to the heirs of the promise the unchangeable character of his purpose, he guaranteed it with an oath" (Heb 6:17). The oath to restore Israel is as secure as the oath of redemption through Christ.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The mountains of Israel shall shoot forth branches and yield fruit for the people Israel — because they are soon to come home. The fruitfulness of the restored land as the sign of homecoming. Christologically, the branches bearing fruit on the mountains of Israel echo Jesus\'s vine-and-branches teaching (John 15:1-8): the eschatological fruitfulness of the land is realized spiritually in the union of believers with Christ, and will be realized physically in the new creation.</p>',
    "9": '<p>YHWH is for the mountains — turning toward them to till and sow. The divine commitment to the physical restoration of the land. Christologically, the God who turns toward the barren mountains is the Father who runs toward the returning prodigal son (Luke 15:20). The divine turning-toward is the initiating act of all restoration.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Multiplying people on the mountains — the cities inhabited, the waste places rebuilt. The demographic restoration: the people returning and filling the land. Christologically, the great commission ("make disciples of all nations") is the eschatological people-multiplication: the church as the new Israel whose numbers fill the earth with the knowledge of God (Hab 2:14; Matt 28:19).</p>',
    "11": '<p>More people and animals than before, prosperous and more numerous than formerly. The restoration exceeds the original — the new creation is greater than the first creation. Christologically, the NT pattern is consistent: Christ gives more than what was lost. "Last Adam" gives more than "first Adam" lost (Rom 5:15: "the free gift is not like the trespass... how much more have the grace of God and the free gift by the grace of that one man Jesus Christ abounded for many").</p>',
    "12": '<p>People walking on the mountains, the land no longer bereaving the nation. The land that "ate" its people (v.13-14) is now a nurturing land. Christologically, the reversal from devouring land to life-giving land mirrors the resurrection: death that devoured life (1 Cor 15:26: "the last enemy to be destroyed is death") is swallowed up by resurrection victory (1 Cor 15:54-55: "death is swallowed up in victory").</p>',
    "13": '<p>The accusation: "You devour men and bereave your nation of children." The land itself accused of consuming its people — the covenantal reversal where the promised land became the devouring land. Christologically, the curse of the devouring land (Lev 26:38: "the land shall devour you") is taken by Christ: "Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us" (Gal 3:13). The devouring curse is absorbed by the one who was devoured by death and rose again.</p>',
    "14": '<p>No more devouring men, no more bereaving the nation — the taunt of the nations ended. The restorative promise for the land. Christologically, the ending of the taunt corresponds to the silencing of the accuser: "the accuser of our brothers has been thrown down" (Rev 12:10). Christ\'s victory ends the enemy\'s claim to use the covenant curses against the covenant people.</p>',
    "15": '<p>No more hearing the reproach of the nations, no longer causing stumbling to the nations. The restoration of covenant honor before the watching world. Christologically, the church\'s calling is to be a community that displays the glory of Christ rather than causing the nations to reproach: "live honorably among the Gentiles, so that... they may see your good deeds and glorify God on the day of visitation" (1 Pet 2:12).</p>',
    "16": '<p>The word of YHWH comes with the explanation of why the exile happened. The oracle pivots from the land\'s restoration to the theological rationale. Christologically, the reason for the exile (covenant unfaithfulness producing judgment) is the exact situation that the cross addresses: "God was in Christ reconciling the world to himself, not counting their trespasses against them" (2 Cor 5:19).</p>',
    "17": '<p>The house of Israel defiled the land by their conduct — like the defilement of a woman\'s menstrual impurity. The strongest language of ritual and moral defilement. Christologically, the comprehensive defilement of the covenant community is precisely the condition that requires the all-sufficient cleansing of Christ\'s blood: "the blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin" (1 John 1:7) — not partial cleansing but comprehensive purification of all defilement.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Pouring out wrath on them because of blood, idols, and defilement. The multiple-category covenant violation. Christologically, the multi-category transgression requires a multi-dimensional redemption: "in him we have redemption through his blood, the forgiveness of our trespasses" (Eph 1:7), covering all categories of offense against the covenant.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Scattered among the nations — judged according to their conduct and deeds. The exile as covenant judgment. Christologically, the scattering of the covenant people creates the precondition for the gathering: "Jesus would die for the nation, and not for the nation only, but also to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad" (John 11:51-52). The scattering is not the end but the preparation for the universal ingathering.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The profanation of YHWH\'s name among the nations — "these are YHWH\'s people, yet they have gone out of his land." The theological scandal: the people of YHWH experiencing covenant judgment appeared to prove YHWH\'s powerlessness or faithlessness to the nations. Christologically, the scandal of the cross is the same: "Christ crucified, a stumbling block to Jews and folly to Gentiles" (1 Cor 1:23). Yet this apparent scandal is "the power of God and the wisdom of God" (1 Cor 1:24).</p>',
    "21": '<p>YHWH has concern for his holy name. The divine motivation for restoration: not primarily the people\'s merit but YHWH\'s own reputation and character. Christologically, this is the basis of salvation by grace alone: "to the praise of his glorious grace" (Eph 1:6) — the ultimate purpose of redemption is the display of YHWH\'s own glory and character, not the reward of human merit.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Not for the sake of the house of Israel but for the sake of the holy name. The explicitly grace-basis of the restoration — merit excluded entirely. Christologically, this is the justification-by-faith principle: "for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God, and are justified by his grace as a gift, through the redemption that is in Christ Jesus" (Rom 3:23-24). Not for our sake but for the sake of the one who redeems.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Sanctifying the great name profaned among the nations — the nations will know YHWH. The universal scope of the name-vindication: all nations will see the covenant kept. Christologically, the sanctification of YHWH\'s name is what Christ accomplishes on the cross. The Lord\'s Prayer opens with "hallowed be your name" — the petition that the cross answers definitively, as God shows himself both just and the justifier (Rom 3:26).</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>The new Exodus gathering</strong>: "I will take you from the nations and gather you from all the countries and bring you into your own land." The eschatological new Exodus — the greatest ingathering. Christologically, this is fulfilled both in the return from exile and ultimately in Christ\'s universal gathering: "I will draw all people to myself" (John 12:32); "he will send out his angels with a loud trumpet call, and they will gather his elect from the four winds" (Matt 24:31). The gathering from all nations through Christ fulfills the scope of v.24.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>The cleansing waters</strong>: "I will sprinkle clean water on you, and you shall be clean from all your uncleannesses, and from all your idols I will cleanse you." The sprinkling of clean water — Christologically the most direct OT anticipation of Christian baptism. The Num 19 purification-water ritual (sprinkled for corpse-impurity) is here elevated to a universal eschatological purification: all uncleannesses and all idols. Titus 3:5: "the washing of regeneration and renewing of the Holy Spirit"; 1 Cor 6:11: "washed... sanctified... justified in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ." The baptismal waters of the new covenant fulfill the sprinkling of v.25.</p>',
    "26": '<p><strong>The new heart and new spirit</strong>: "And I will give you a new heart, and a new spirit I will put within you. And I will remove the heart of stone from your flesh and give you a heart of flesh." This is the most direct OT statement of regeneration — the new birth Jesus describes in John 3:3-8. The heart of stone (impermeable to divine influence) replaced by the heart of flesh (responsive to YHWH) is the work of the Spirit through the gospel. Paul: "you are a letter from Christ... written not with ink but with the Spirit of the living God, not on tablets of stone but on tablets of human hearts" (2 Cor 3:3). The stony law-tablets replaced by the fleshy-heart Spirit-tablets — Ezekiel 36:26 in Pauline register.</p>',
    "28": '<p><strong>Covenant renewal: you shall be my people</strong>: "You shall dwell in the land that I gave to your fathers, and you shall be my people, and I will be your God." The covenant formula (<em>ani YHWH eloheikhem</em>) — "I will be your God and you shall be my people" — running through Lev 26:12, Jer 31:33, Ezek 36:28, is the heartbeat of the covenant. Christologically, this covenant formula is fulfilled in the new covenant community: "I will be their God and they shall be my people" (Heb 8:10, quoting Jer 31:33); "I will dwell in them and walk among them, and I will be their God, and they shall be my people" (2 Cor 6:16); ultimately in Rev 21:3: "the dwelling place of God is with man. He will dwell with them, and they will be his people, and God himself will be with them as their God."</p>',
    "29": '<p>Delivering from uncleanness, summoning grain and multiplying it. The complete restoration of agricultural abundance. Christologically, the abundance promised here points to the new creation\'s fruitfulness: the earth that cursed the first Adam (Gen 3:17-19) is released from its curse in Christ (Rev 22:3: "no longer will there be anything accursed"). The grain multiplication anticipates the feeding of the five thousand (John 6:1-14) — the messianic sign of covenant abundance.</p>',
    "30": '<p>Fruit of the tree and produce of the field multiplied — no more famine among the nations. The reversal of the covenant curse (Lev 26:20: "your land shall not yield its produce") through covenant restoration. Christologically, the bread-of-life teaching (John 6:35: "I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger") is the spiritual fulfillment of the grain and fruit abundance that Ezekiel 36:30 promises for the new covenant era.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Remembering evil ways and deeds that were not good, loathing yourselves. The shame of restoration — not triumphalism but genuine self-knowledge in the light of grace. Christologically, the post-resurrection community of Peter and the disciples models this: Peter wept bitterly after the denial (Luke 22:62); the post-resurrection meeting includes restoration despite shame (John 21:15-19). Grace creates self-knowledge, not self-congratulation.</p>',
    "32": '<p><strong>Not for your sake</strong>: "It is not for your sake that I will act, declares the Lord YHWH; let that be known to you. Be ashamed and confounded for your ways, O house of Israel." The double negation of human merit: not for your sake, and shame is the appropriate response to grace. Christologically, this is the heart of the theology of grace: salvation is entirely YHWH\'s initiative, for YHWH\'s glory, so that human shame before grace produces gratitude rather than pride. "By grace you have been saved through faith. And this is not your own doing; it is the gift of God, not a result of works, so that no one may boast" (Eph 2:8-9).</p>',
    "33": '<p>On the day of cleansing, cities inhabited and waste places rebuilt. The day of cleansing as the beginning of restoration. Christologically, "the day of cleansing" is the cross: "the blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin" (1 John 1:7) — the day of ultimate cleansing inaugurates the building of the new temple community. "You are being built together into a dwelling place for God by the Spirit" (Eph 2:22).</p>',
    "34": '<p>The desolate land tilled instead of being a desolation in the sight of all who passed by. The restoration visible to observers. Christologically, the church as the renewed covenant community is visible evidence of divine restoration: "you are a letter from Christ... to be known and read by all" (2 Cor 3:2-3). The tilled-and-fruitful land = the Spirit-transformed community of believers whose lives are the visible sign of the new covenant\'s reality.</p>',
    "35": '<p><strong>Like the Garden of Eden</strong>: "They will say: this land that was desolate has become like the garden of Eden, and the waste and desolate and ruined cities are now inhabited and fortified." The Eden comparison is the new-creation comparison: the restored land surpasses the original creation by being explicitly compared to Eden. Christologically, Christ as the last Adam (1 Cor 15:45) restores and surpasses what the first Adam lost. The new Jerusalem of Revelation 21-22 is explicitly Eden-imagery: the river of life, the tree of life, the removal of the curse — Ezekiel 36:35 is the transitional promise between Eden and the New Jerusalem.</p>',
    "36": '<p>The nations around knowing that YHWH rebuilt and replanted. The universal recognition of the divine work. Christologically, the church among the nations is the ongoing sign of YHWH\'s rebuilding: "by this all people will know that you are my disciples, if you have love for one another" (John 13:35). The covenant community\'s visible transformation is the evidence that makes the nations say "YHWH has done this."</p>',
    "37": '<p>YHWH\'s declaration: "I have spoken and I will do it." The absolute divine commitment — word and action unified. Christologically, Christ is the Word become flesh (John 1:14) — the ultimate unity of divine word and divine action. The promise that YHWH speaks and will perform is fulfilled in the one who is himself both the promise and its fulfillment: "all the promises of God find their Yes in him" (2 Cor 1:20).</p>',
    "38": '<p>Israel praying for the rebuilding — "let the house of Israel pray for this to be done for them." The prayer of the covenant community as the mechanism of receiving the promised restoration. Christologically, this grounds the eschatological promises in prayer: "Ask, and it will be given to you" (Matt 7:7); "the prayer of a righteous person has great power as it is working" (Jas 5:16). The church prays "your kingdom come" (Matt 6:10) as the corporate Ezekiel 36:37 prayer — requesting the new-creation fullness that YHWH has promised to give.'
},
"37": {
    "1": '<p><strong>The valley of dry bones — the most direct resurrection text in the OT</strong>: "The hand of YHWH was upon me, and he brought me out in the Spirit of YHWH and set me down in the middle of the valley; it was full of bones." The vision of the valley full of bones is the most vivid resurrection-vision in the OT, cited across the NT to illuminate the resurrection of Christ and believers. Ephesians 2:1-6 is the direct NT application: "you were dead in your trespasses and sins... but God... made us alive together with Christ."</p>',
    "2": '<p>Very many bones on the surface of the valley — extremely dry. The dryness of the bones emphasizes the completeness of the death: not recently dead but long dead, all moisture and life entirely gone. Christologically, the human condition before Christ is not merely sick or weak but dead: "even when we were dead in our trespasses" (Eph 2:5). The absolute dryness is the precondition for the absolute miracle — resurrection from the most extreme deadness.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Son of man, can these bones live?" The divine question to Ezekiel. The humanly unanswerable question — from a natural standpoint, no: the bones are beyond any human restoration. Ezekiel wisely answers: "O Lord YHWH, you know." Christologically, this is the pattern of faith: when the question is whether the dead can live, the only answer is "you know" — the acknowledgment that resurrection is in God\'s hands alone. The disciples at the tomb could not have answered "can this body live?" except by trusting the one who said "I am the resurrection and the life" (John 11:25).</p>',
    "4": '<p>YHWH commands Ezekiel to prophesy to the bones: "O dry bones, hear the word of YHWH." The prophetic word spoken to what is dead — the word that creates as it speaks. Christologically, "the hour is coming and is now here, when the dead will hear the voice of the Son of God, and those who hear will live" (John 5:25). The prophetic command to dry bones is fulfilled in the Son of Man\'s resurrection-summons to the dead.</p>',
    "5": '<p>YHWH will cause breath (<em>ruach</em>) to enter the bones and they will live. The <em>ruach</em> (breath/wind/Spirit) as the agent of resurrection — the same Spirit who brooded over the waters of creation (Gen 1:2). Christologically, the resurrection of Jesus is explicitly a Spirit-work: "he was put to death in the flesh but made alive in the spirit" (1 Pet 3:18); "if the Spirit of him who raised Jesus from the dead dwells in you, he who raised Christ Jesus from the dead will also give life to your mortal bodies through his Spirit who dwells in you" (Rom 8:11).</p>',
    "6": '<p>Sinews on the bones, flesh covered, skin over it, breath put within — they will live and know YHWH. The step-by-step reconstitution: bones → sinews → flesh → skin → breath. The progressive resurrection stages mirror the eschatological resurrection: "the body is sown in dishonor; it is raised in glory" (1 Cor 15:43); the perishable clothed with the imperishable (1 Cor 15:53-54). The end of the resurrection process — they will live and know YHWH — is the Johannine definition of eternal life: "this is eternal life, that they know you, the only true God" (John 17:3).</p>',
    "7": '<p>Ezekiel prophesied as commanded; a rattling sound and bones came together. The word-of-prophecy as the mechanism of physical reconstitution. Christologically, "faith comes from hearing, and hearing through the word of Christ" (Rom 10:17) — the same word-mechanism. The gospel proclaimed creates the spiritual life it announces, just as the prophetic word to the bones creates the physical reconstitution it describes.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Sinews and flesh came on the bones, skin covered them, but no breath yet. The bodily reconstitution without the breath — an almost-resurrection, not yet complete. Christologically, this stage reminds us that bodily existence without the Spirit of God is not yet resurrection-life. The disciples before Pentecost are in this stage: gathered, formed, instructed — but not yet filled with the resurrection-breath of the Spirit (John 20:22; Acts 2:1-4).</p>',
    "9": '<p>YHWH commands Ezekiel to prophesy to the <em>ruach</em> (breath/wind/Spirit) from the four winds to breathe into the slain. The command to the Spirit to come from all four directions — the cosmic comprehensiveness of the Spirit\'s work. Christologically, this "breath from the four winds" anticipates Pentecost: "suddenly there came from heaven a sound like a mighty rushing wind, and it filled the entire house where they were sitting" (Acts 2:2). The wind of the Spirit fulfills the vision of Ezekiel 37:9.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The breath came, they lived, and stood on their feet — an exceedingly great army. The resurrection from the valley creates an army. Christologically, the resurrection community is called to be God\'s "army" in the spiritual sense: "put on the whole armor of God" (Eph 6:11); "fight the good fight of the faith" (1 Tim 6:12). The exceedingly great army of Ezekiel 37:10 is the resurrection-community of believers who will ultimately number as the stars of heaven (Rev 7:9).</p>',
    "11": '<p>The bones are the whole house of Israel — their bones are dried, their hope lost, they are cut off. The explicit interpretation: the dry bones = Israel in exile. "Our hope is lost" and "we are cut off" — the double death-declaration of the covenant community. Christologically, this is the disciples\' experience after the crucifixion: "we had hoped that he was the one to redeem Israel" (Luke 24:21). The past-tense "had hoped" is the disciples\' Ezekiel 37:11 moment, answered by the resurrection morning.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>I will open your graves and raise you from your graves</strong>: "Therefore prophesy, and say to them, Thus says the Lord YHWH: Behold, I will open your graves and raise you from your graves, O my people." The first explicit grave-opening language applied to Israel. Jesus quotes the grave-opening expectation in John 5:28-29: "an hour is coming when all who are in the tombs will hear his voice and come out." The divine grave-opening of Ezekiel 37:12 is accomplished by the voice of the Son of Man at the general resurrection.</p>',
    "13": '<p>They shall know YHWH when he opens their graves and raises them. The recognition formula at resurrection — the knowledge of YHWH obtained through the experience of resurrection. Christologically, "if Christ has not been raised, your faith is futile and you are still in your sins" (1 Cor 15:17) — the resurrection is the evidence that confirms the identity of Jesus as Lord. The raised people of Ezekiel 37:13 "know YHWH"; the risen church "knows Jesus is Lord" (Rom 10:9: "if you confess with your mouth that Jesus is Lord and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved").</p>',
    "14": '<p>YHWH\'s Spirit put within them — they live and are placed in their land. The Spirit as the means of resurrection-life in the covenant land. Christologically, this is the Pentecost fulfillment: the Spirit given to the resurrected community who now inhabit the new-covenant "land" — the people of God gathered from all nations. The Spirit within them (Ezek 36:27) produces the life that the Spirit breathed into them (37:14) — the two Spirit-promises complement each other.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The two-sticks vision — Ezekiel takes two sticks, writes the kingdoms on them. The sign-act of the two sticks is the enacted prophecy of national reunification. Christologically, the division of the covenant community (north/south, Jew/Greek, circumcision/uncircumcision) is healed in Christ: "he himself is our peace, who has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility... that he might create in himself one new man in place of the two" (Eph 2:14-15).</p>',
    "16": '<p>The stick for Judah and the stick for Joseph (Ephraim/Israel). The two sticks representing the divided kingdom. The division is historical and real — the Assyrian exile of the northern kingdom in 722 BCE. Christologically, the deeper division that Christ heals is between humanity and God: "the dividing wall of hostility" (Eph 2:14) is ultimately the sin-separation of Isa 59:2. The two-stick reunion is the visible sign of the deeper God-humanity reunion in Christ.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The two sticks become one in the hand of Ezekiel. The sign-act of unification — two become one in the prophet\'s hand. Christologically, the one body of Christ is the fulfillment: "there is one body and one Spirit... one Lord, one faith, one baptism, one God and Father of all" (Eph 4:4-6). The unity of the two sticks becomes the unity of the one new humanity in Christ.</p>',
    "18": '<p>When the people ask what this means, Ezekiel is ready to explain. The sign-act generates the question that allows the divine word to be received. Christologically, this is the pedagogical pattern of all prophetic signs: they create inquiry that allows revelation. Jesus uses the same pattern: his miracles generate questions ("Who then is this?" Mark 4:41) that allow fuller teaching about his identity.</p>',
    "19": '<p>YHWH will take the stick of Joseph and join it with Judah\'s stick — making them one stick. The divine first-person unification: "I will make them one." The reunification is YHWH\'s act, not human political achievement. Christologically, the unity of the church is similarly divine: "that they may all be one, just as you, Father, are in me, and I in you, that they also may be in us" (John 17:21). The Ezekiel 37:19 unification is fulfilled in the trinitarian-unity prayer of John 17.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Hold the sticks before their eyes. The visual evidence of the sign-act maintained for the audience. Christologically, the visible signs that confirm divine word are a consistent biblical pattern. Thomas\'s insistence on seeing the risen Christ (John 20:25) is answered by Christ showing his hands and side: the visible evidence confirming the resurrection-word. "Blessed are those who have not seen and yet have believed" (John 20:29) points beyond the visible sign to the faith it generates.</p>',
    "21": '<p>YHWH gathering Israel from among the nations and bringing them into their land — the second mention of the new Exodus in the chapter (cf. 36:24). The repeated gathering promise emphasizes its certainty and its scope. Christologically, this is the universal gathering that John 11:52 describes as Jesus\'s ultimate purpose: "to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad." The scattered covenant people — both Jewish and gentile believers — are gathered into the one body through Christ.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>One nation under one king</strong>: "And I will make them one nation in the land, on the mountains of Israel. And one king shall be king over them all, and they shall be no longer two nations, and no longer divided into two kingdoms." The Messianic-king who unifies the divided covenant community. Christologically, "one king shall be king over them all" = Christ as the Lord of the unified church. "There is one Lord" (Eph 4:5); "there is one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus" (1 Tim 2:5). The one king of Ezekiel 37:22 is the risen and ascended Christ.</p>',
    "23": '<p>They shall not defile themselves with idols, detestable things, or transgressions — YHWH will save them from all apostasies. The purification that accompanies the reunification. Christologically, sanctification accompanies justification: "to him who loves us and has freed us from our sins by his blood" (Rev 1:5) — the freedom from sin is integral to the new-covenant promise. The community that YHWH saves from its apostasies is the community Christ sanctifies: "Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her, that he might sanctify her" (Eph 5:25-26).</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>David my servant shall be king</strong>: "My servant David shall be king over them, and they shall all have one shepherd." The Messianic David-king who is also the shepherd. This dual title — king and shepherd — is uniquely royal-pastoral. Christologically, Jesus is "the good shepherd" (John 10:11, 14) and "King of kings and Lord of lords" (Rev 19:16) simultaneously. "David my servant" (cf. Jer 23:5-6; 33:15-16) is the Messianic figure who gathers all the earlier Davidic promises into one fulfillment.</p>',
    "25": '<p>They shall dwell in the land forever — the servant David shall be their prince forever. The eternal duration of the Messianic kingdom. Christologically, "of his kingdom there will be no end" (Luke 1:33) — the angel\'s announcement to Mary directly fulfills Ezekiel 37:25. The eternal king of the eternal covenant rules the permanently gathered people in the permanent land. The "forever" (<em>le\'olam</em>) of Ezekiel 37:25 is the eschatological eternity of Revelation 22:5: "they will reign forever and ever."</p>',
    "26": '<p><strong>The eternal covenant of peace</strong>: "I will make a covenant of peace with them. It shall be an everlasting covenant with them. And I will set them in their land and multiply them, and will set my sanctuary in their midst forevermore." The <em>brit shalom</em> (covenant of peace) of the new covenant. Christologically, "he himself is our peace, who has made us both one" (Eph 2:14); "peace be with you" (John 20:19, 21, 26) — the resurrection greeting of the risen Christ who has made the covenant of peace through his blood (Col 1:20: "making peace by the blood of his cross").</p>',
    "27": '<p><strong>My dwelling place shall be with them</strong>: "My dwelling place shall be with them, and I will be their God, and they shall be my people." The fullest expression of the covenant formula — "I will dwell with them." Christologically, this is fulfilled in stages: (1) the Incarnation (John 1:14: "the Word became flesh and <em>dwelt</em> [<em>eskēnōsen</em> = tabernacled] among us"); (2) the Spirit indwelling the church (1 Cor 3:16: "God\'s Spirit dwells in you"); (3) the New Jerusalem (Rev 21:3: "the dwelling place of God is with man"). The three stages of divine dwelling-with-humanity are all expressed in Ezekiel 37:27\'s promise.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The nations shall know that YHWH sanctifies Israel when his sanctuary is in their midst forevermore. The universal recognition of the covenant — YHWH\'s relationship with Israel made visible to all nations through the permanent sanctuary. Christologically, the universal recognition of YHWH through the sanctified community is the church\'s mission: "you shall be my witnesses in Jerusalem and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the end of the earth" (Acts 1:8). The permanent sanctuary in the midst = the church as the temple of the Holy Spirit bearing witness to all nations.'
},
"38": {
    "1": '<p>The oracle against Gog of the land of Magog opens with the standard prophetic formula. Gog and Magog represent the eschatological enemy — the supreme anti-covenant coalition at the end of history. Christologically, Revelation 20:7-10 identifies "Gog and Magog" as the final gathering of all nations against the beloved city at the end of the millennium — the last great assault on the covenant community before the final judgment and new creation. Ezekiel 38-39 is the OT source text for Revelation\'s eschatological battle.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Gog, chief prince of Meshech and Tubal — the leader of the coalition. The identity of Gog has been debated for centuries (Scythians, Medes, Russia — none certain). Christologically, the specifics matter less than the theological pattern: there is always an ultimate enemy of the covenant community, gathering all anti-Kingdom forces for a final assault. This enemy encounters not human military resistance but direct divine intervention — which is the pattern of all the battles where YHWH fights for his people.</p>',
    "3": '<p>YHWH is against Gog. The divine opposition stated at the beginning: "I am against you, O Gog." YHWH\'s "against" is as certain as his "for." Christologically, Christ is both for his people (Rom 8:31: "if God is for us, who can be against us?") and against those who oppose his kingdom: "to those who are disobedient... he is a stone of stumbling and a rock of offense" (1 Pet 2:7-8). The same Christ who is the cornerstone for believers is the stone of judgment for those who oppose the Kingdom.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Gog turned about and led out by YHWH — hooks put in his jaws, leading him and his army. The paradox of the enemy\'s "free" aggression being simultaneously the instrument of divine purpose. Christologically, this is the theological pattern of the cross: "this Jesus, delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God, you crucified and killed by the hands of lawless men" (Acts 2:23). The enemy\'s most destructive act is within divine sovereignty — not eliminating moral responsibility but incorporating it into redemptive purpose.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Persia, Cush, and Put with him — multinational forces. The global coalition against YHWH\'s people. Christologically, the universal scope of the opposition corresponds to the universal scope of Christ\'s victory: "he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him" (Col 2:15). The multinational forces that Gog assembles are the very powers Christ publicly disarms at the cross.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Gomer, the house of Togarmah from the far north with all its troops. The geographic comprehensiveness — from the far north. The global assembly of the forces of opposition. Christologically, the comprehensive gathering of enemies is overcome by the comprehensive gathering of worshippers: "a great multitude that no one could number, from every nation, from all tribes and peoples and languages, standing before the throne" (Rev 7:9). The nations gathered against YHWH are answered by the nations gathered in worship before the Lamb.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Be ready and keep ready — Gog as the guardian and reserve for the assault. The instructions to Gog presuppose divine control of the enemy\'s timing and readiness. Christologically, the timing of God\'s eschatological acts is entirely within divine control: "but concerning that day and hour no one knows, not even the angels of heaven, nor the Son, but the Father only" (Matt 24:36). The enemy prepares on YHWH\'s schedule, not its own.</p>',
    "8": '<p>In latter days Gog will come against the restored land and people. The eschatological framing: "in the latter days" (<em>be\'acharit hayamim</em>) — the standard OT phrase for the messianic age or its culmination. Christologically, the "latter days" have already begun with the incarnation (Heb 1:2: "in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son"; Acts 2:17: "in the last days... I will pour out my Spirit"). Gog\'s attack in the latter days is the final assault of the anti-Kingdom forces in the era inaugurated by Christ.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Gog comes like a storm, like a cloud covering the land. The overwhelming military force — sheer scale. Christologically, the apparently overwhelming nature of the enemy\'s assault is the background for the NT assurance: "neither death nor life, nor angels nor rulers, nor things present nor things to come, nor powers, nor height nor depth, nor anything else in all creation, will be able to separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus our Lord" (Rom 8:38-39). The storm of Gog cannot overcome the love of Christ.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Evil plans form in Gog\'s mind. The cognitive origin of the eschatological assault — the strategy of the enemy. Christologically, "the thief comes only to steal and kill and destroy" (John 10:10) — the destructive strategy of the adversary is countered by Christ who "came that they may have life and have it abundantly." The plans that "form in Gog\'s mind" are the same evil strategies that Paul identifies as "schemes of the devil" (Eph 6:11) to be resisted with the full armor of God.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Go against the land of unwalled villages — the peaceful, unsuspecting people. The attack against the vulnerable and undefended covenant community. Christologically, the church\'s vulnerability to worldly power is matched by the divine protection: "though we walk in the flesh, we are not waging war according to the flesh. For the weapons of our warfare are not of the flesh but have divine power to destroy strongholds" (2 Cor 10:3-4). The defenses of God\'s people are not walls but the divine power that fights on their behalf.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Seizing spoil and plunder, attacking restored ruins now inhabited, the people gathered from the nations. The target of Gog\'s assault: the regathered covenant community at the center of the nations. Christologically, the assault on the church gathered from all nations mirrors the opposition Paul encounters throughout Acts — the eschatological battle is the intensification of the constant spiritual warfare that has characterized the entire church age (1 Pet 5:8: "your adversary the devil prowls around like a roaring lion").</p>',
    "13": '<p>Sheba, Dedan, merchants of Tarshish with their villages asking if Gog comes for plunder. The bystander nations watching — merchants calculating profit. The observation of the cosmic battle by commercial powers. Christologically, the global commercial power of "Babylon" in Revelation 18 is described in similarly mercantile terms — the nations enriched by Babylon\'s trade (Rev 18:11-17). The mercantile observers of Ezekiel 38:13 become the lamenting merchants of Revelation 18 when the eschatological judgment falls.</p>',
    "14": '<p>YHWH addresses Gog directly: on the day my people Israel dwell securely, Gog will be aware and come. The security of the covenant community as the occasion for the final assault. Christologically, the church\'s security in Christ is precisely what provokes the enemy\'s final assault: "the gates of hell will not prevail against it" (Matt 16:18) — Christ\'s confident declaration that the church\'s security is indestructible. The enemy comes against the secure church and finds that its security is divine, not human.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Gog comes from the far north with his great army of many peoples. The global scope of the anti-covenant coalition assembled. Christologically, this north-axis assault is the geographical expression of the cosmic spiritual reality: "our struggle is not against flesh and blood, but against the rulers, against the authorities, against the cosmic powers over this present darkness, against the spiritual forces of evil in the heavenly places" (Eph 6:12). The army from the north is the spatial expression of the spiritual anti-Kingdom reality.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Coming against YHWH\'s people like a cloud covering the land — and in latter days YHWH will be vindicated through Gog in the eyes of the nations. The purpose of allowing the assault: divine vindication. Christologically, the cross is the supreme event of apparent defeat that becomes divine vindication. "Christ died for our sins in accordance with the Scriptures" — the apparent victory of the enemy is the actual moment of YHWH\'s most complete self-revelation as Savior.</p>',
    "17": '<p>YHWH asks: are you the one of whom I spoke in former times by my servants the prophets? The connection to previous prophecies about the ultimate enemy. Christologically, the continuity of the prophetic witness is the continuity of the Christ-promise: "in many and various ways God spoke to our fathers by the prophets, but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son" (Heb 1:1-2). The prophetic preparation for the eschatological battle is also the prophetic preparation for the eschatological Savior.</p>',
    "18": '<p>YHWH\'s fury will mount on that day of Gog\'s invasion. The divine wrath against the final anti-Kingdom coalition. Christologically, the wrath of God against all ungodliness and unrighteousness (Rom 1:18) is concentrated in the final judgment. But that same wrath was also concentrated at the cross: "God presented Christ as a propitiation" (Rom 3:25) — the eschatological wrath that falls on Gog was already poured out on the Servant who bore the sins of the many (Isa 53:11-12).</p>',
    "19": '<p>YHWH declares in fiery passion — a great earthquake in the land of Israel on that day. The eschatological earthquake accompanying divine intervention. Christologically, earthquakes accompany the key moments of Christ\'s redeeming work: the crucifixion (Matt 27:51-54), the resurrection (Matt 28:2), and the end of the age (Rev 6:12; 11:13; 16:18). The eschatological earthquake of Ezekiel 38:19 is part of the pattern of cosmic disruption that accompanies divine self-revelation in judgment and salvation.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Fish, birds, beasts, creeping things, and all people on the face of the earth shall quake before YHWH. The universal scope of the earthquake — no part of creation is unaffected. Christologically, "every knee shall bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth" (Phil 2:10) is the salvation-side of this universal quaking. The same cosmic shaking that accompanies judgment becomes, for those in Christ, the arrival of the unshakeable kingdom: "let us be grateful for receiving a kingdom that cannot be shaken" (Heb 12:28).</p>',
    "21": '<p>YHWH summons a sword against Gog throughout all my mountains — every man\'s sword against his brother. The divine self-defeat of the enemy coalition: YHWH turns Gog\'s forces against each other. Christologically, the self-destruction of the enemy is the pattern of demonic opposition: "every kingdom divided against itself is laid waste, and no city or house divided against itself will stand" (Matt 12:25). The sword that YHWH summons on Gog is the sword of divine judgment that the enemy cannot withstand.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Judgment through pestilence, blood, rain, fire, and sulfur — the comprehensive covenant curse catalog. The six forms of divine judgment recall the plagues of Egypt and the destruction of Sodom (fire and sulfur). Christologically, the comprehensive judgment-catalog is the negative image of the comprehensive salvation-catalog: "in him we have redemption through his blood, the forgiveness of our trespasses... the riches of his grace" (Eph 1:7). The comprehensive curses of covenant judgment find their comprehensive answer in the comprehensive grace of Christ.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>YHWH magnified, sanctified, and made known before many nations — and they shall know YHWH</strong>: The eschatological conclusion: "so I will show my greatness and my holiness and make myself known in the eyes of many nations. Then they shall know that I am YHWH." The recognition formula at cosmic scope — all nations knowing YHWH through the defeat of the ultimate enemy. Christologically, this is fulfilled in the exaltation of Christ: "God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above every name, so that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth, and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the glory of God the Father" (Phil 2:9-11). The universal knowing of YHWH through the defeat of Gog = the universal acknowledgment of Christ as Lord through his defeat of death.</p>'
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezekiel')
    merge_comm(existing, EZEKIEL_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezekiel', existing)
    print('Ezekiel 36-38 mkt-christ commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
